islets?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Delta cells produce insulin while beta cells produce somatostatin","PP cells produce glucagon while alpha cells produce pancreatic polypeptide","Alpha cells produce insulin to lower blood glucose","Beta cells produce insulin to lower blood glucose while alpha cells produce glucagon to raise blood glucose","Beta cells produce glucagon to raise blood glucose"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPancreatic islets contain several distinct cell types with specific hormone-producing functions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlpha cells\u003C/strong\u003E produce glucagon, which raises blood glucose by promoting glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta cells\u003C/strong\u003E produce insulin, which lowers blood glucose by promoting glucose uptake and storage\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelta cells\u003C/strong\u003E produce somatostatin, which inhibits both insulin and glucagon release\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPP cells\u003C/strong\u003E produce pancreatic polypeptide, which regulates pancreatic secretion and appetite\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe coordinated function of these cells, particularly the opposing actions of insulin and glucagon, is essential for maintaining blood glucose homeostasis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pancreatic islet cells contain distinct cell types that produce different hormones: alpha cells produce glucagon, beta cells produce insulin, delta cells produce somatostatin, and PP cells produce pancreatic polypeptide.","The endocrine pancreas regulates glucose homeostasis through the opposing actions of insulin and glucagon."],"references":["Nightingale, J. M. (2012). Applied anatomy and physiology of the gastrointestinal tract (GIT). Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book: Gastrointestinal Tr